what is toyota AE86?
The AE86 generation of the Toyota Corolla Levin and Toyota Sprinter Trueno is a small, lightweight coupe introduced by Toyota in 1983 as part of the fifth generation Toyota Corolla lineup. For the purpose of brevity, the insider-chassis code of "AE86" depicts the 1600 cc RWD model from the range. In classic Toyota code, the "A" represents the engine that came in the car (4A series), "E" represents the Corolla, "8" represents the fifth generation (E80 series) and "6" represents the variation within this generation.

The Levin has fixed-headlights, and the Trueno has retractable headlights, both could be hatchback or coupe. The export model name Corolla covers both variations. The AE86 (along with the lower spec 1,452 cubic centimetres (1.452 L) AE85 and 1587 cc SR5 versions) was rear wheel drive (unlike the front wheel drive CE80, EE80 and AE82 models), and is among the last rear-drive cars of its type, at a time when most passenger cars were being switched to front-drive. In 1987, there was a limited edition model of the AE86 called "Black Limited" that served as a send-off model before the AE86 chassis was replaced later that year by the front wheel drive AE92 Corolla/Sprinter range.
In Japan, the AE86 was also known as the Hachi-Roku (ハチロク?), Japanese for "eight-six". In Japan, the Sprinter Trueno was exclusive to Toyota Japan dealerships called Toyota Vista Store, while the Corolla Levin was exclusive to Toyota Corolla Store. The word "trueno" is Spanish for thunder, and "levin" is Old English for "lightning".

When Mercedes first introduced the CLS to the market, the idea of ​​a 4-door coupe seemed very interesting to everyone. However, now the eyes have become accustomed to this vehicle structure and the lines of the model have begun to look like an extended GT, so it no longer seems odd.

CLS, which has become a much more aggressive car compared to the leading models, is designed with the aggressive lines that the company started to use in its new generation. New brand lines are used on both the front and rear of the vehicle. CLS, which has an aggressive appearance with its body low to the ground and short bumper-wheel distance, is perceived as a real coupe at first when dark colors are preferred, as in the test vehicle. This is a significant plus for him.

The lines of the vehicle are so effectively hidden in the new design language that the 18-inch wheels are perceived as smaller and disappear into the fenders.The interior of the Mercedes CLS is prepared under the dominance of common parts, as in the leading models. Of course, this situation will not please those who want originality. However, you feel the quality and high workmanship in the interior as soon as you open the door. Thanks to the customizable interior, you can create a version that suits your taste.

However, unfortunately, the coupe body brings with it small windows and limited living space. Although the wheelbase of the CLS is close to 3 meters, the interior offers living space for 4 people. Also, headroom is not very good. Offering a huge loading area of ​​520 liters at the back of the vehicle makes it a good long-distance companion.

The interior of the CLS offers a very quiet living space despite the doors without slats. Moreover, even as the speed increases, neither wind nor tire noise comes through the windows.

Tesla, Inc. is an American multinational corporation known for its innovative approach to electric vehicles (EVs), clean energy solutions, and advanced technologies. Electric Vehicles (EVs):

Tesla is renowned for its electric cars, which emphasize long range, high performance, and cutting-edge technology. Its current lineup includes:

Model S: A luxury sedan offering high performance and long range.

Model 3: An affordable, mass-market sedan with impressive range and technology.

Model X: A high-end SUV with unique falcon-wing doors.

Model Y: A compact SUV that combines functionality with efficiency.

Cybertruck: An electric pickup truck with a futuristic design, set for production.

Roadster (2nd Gen): A supercar promised to be the fastest production car, still under development.

Energy Products:

Tesla is also a key player in renewable energy through its subsidiary SolarCity. Its energy products include:

Solar Panels and Solar Roofs: Integrated solar solutions for homes and businesses.

Powerwall: A home battery for energy storage, enabling energy independence.

Powerpack and Megapack: Large-scale energy storage systems for businesses and utilities.

Autonomous Driving:

Tesla develops advanced driver-assistance systems under the name "Autopilot" and "Full Self-Driving (FSD)." While not yet fully autonomous, these systems include features like lane-keeping, adaptive cruise control, and traffic-aware navigation.

Gigafactories:

Gigafactory Nevada (batteries and powertrains)

Gigafactory Shanghai (Model 3 and Model Y production for Asia)

Gigafactory Berlin (European production hub)

Gigafactory Texas (Cybertruck and more)

Tesla has been instrumental in advancing battery technology, EV infrastructure (e.g., Supercharger network), and sustainable energy systems.

Day #17

Saint Telemachus also known as Almachus was a monk who, according to the Church historian Theodoret, tried to stop a gladiatorial fight in a Roman amphitheatre, and was stoned to death by the crowd. The Christian Emperor Honorius, however, was impressed by the monk's martyrdom and it spurred him to issue a historic ban on gladiatorial fights. Frederick George Holweck gives the year of his death as 391.
He is described as being an ascetic who came to Rome from the East. The story is found in the writings of Theodoret, Bishop of Cyrrhus, Syria.
Although the site of Telemachus' martyrdom is often given as being the Colosseum in Rome, Theodoret does not actually specify where it happened, saying merely that it happened in "the stadium".
Later retellings of the story have differed from Theodoret's in a number of details. Foxe's Book of Martyrs claims that Telemachus was first stabbed to death by a gladiator, but that the sight of his death "turned the hearts of the people".

Bacon Cinnamon Rolls

Ingredients
1 can refrigerated cinnamon roll dough (with icing)
6-8 slices of bacon (or as many as there are cinnamon rolls)
Optional: maple syrup for drizzling

Instructions

	1.	Preheat the Oven: Preheat your oven to the temperature indicated on the cinnamon roll package (usually around 350°F or 175°C).
	2.	Cook the Bacon: Partially cook the bacon in a skillet over medium heat until it’s about halfway cooked but still flexible. Remove and drain on paper towels.
	3.	Assemble the Rolls: Unroll each cinnamon roll slightly and place one piece of partially cooked bacon along the dough. Roll it back up, enclosing the bacon.
	4.	Bake: Place the bacon cinnamon rolls in a baking dish and bake according to the package instructions, or until the rolls are golden brown and cooked through.
	5.	Ice and Serve: Drizzle with the icing that came with the cinnamon rolls. For extra flavor, add a drizzle of maple syrup over the top if desired.
	6.	Enjoy: Serve warm and enjoy this sweet and savory treat.

Freak ah roaches Here are some freaky facts about roaches:
	1.	They Can Survive Decapitation – A cockroach can live for weeks without its head. It doesn’t need its brain to breathe, as it relies on spiracles (tiny holes in its body) for oxygen. It eventually dies from dehydration.
	2.	They Can Hold Their Breath for 40 Minutes – Cockroaches can survive underwater for up to 30 minutes by shutting down their spiracles, which helps them conserve water.
	3.	They Can Survive Nuclear Radiation – While they wouldn’t survive a direct nuclear blast, cockroaches can endure radiation levels 10–15 times higher than humans.
	4.	Some Roaches Glow in the Dark – The Luchihormetica luckae cockroach, found in Ecuador, has bioluminescent patches that glow in the dark to mimic toxic beetles and avoid predators.
	5.	They Can Run at 3.4 mph – That might not sound fast, but given their tiny size, it’s like a human running 200 mph! They can also pivot directions in a fraction of a second.
	6.	The “Zombie Roach” Phenomenon – The emerald cockroach wasp injects venom into a cockroach’s brain, turning it into a zombie-like state. The wasp then leads the roach to its burrow and lays eggs on it. When the larvae hatch, they eat the roach alive.
	7.	There’s a Giant Cockroach That Can Live 10 Years – The Megaloblatta longipennis has the longest wingspan of any cockroach (up to 8 inches), and the Giant Burrowing Cockroach of Australia can live up to a decade!
	8.	Cockroaches Fart Constantly – Some species produce methane and can release gas every 15 minutes. They’re low-key contributing to global warming.

Bobby Lee is a comedian, actor, and podcast host known for his distinctive humor and unapologetic personality. He first gained widespread recognition as a cast member on the sketch comedy show *MADtv*, where he showcased his talent for playing eccentric and often outrageous characters. Over the years, Bobby’s style has evolved, moving from traditional sketch comedy to stand-up, as well as branching out into podcasting. He is the host of *TigerBelly*, a popular podcast where he candidly discusses everything from personal anecdotes to deeper mental health topics, often with his girlfriend, Khalyla Kuhn, and various guests. His vulnerability and willingness to be open about his struggles with mental health, addiction, and his upbringing have endeared him to fans, who appreciate his raw honesty.

Beyond his work in comedy, Bobby Lee has also appeared in a variety of film and TV roles, including *Harold & Kumar Go to White Castle* and *The Dollop* podcast, which helped him build a dedicated fanbase outside of his comedy roots. Bobby’s unique blend of self-deprecating humor, cultural commentary, and unfiltered takes has made him a standout figure in the entertainment world. Despite his fame, he’s known for maintaining an everyman charm, which has kept him relatable to a wide audience. His willingness to push boundaries, both in his humor and his personal life, has made him an influential voice in modern comedy.

The Langlands Program is a deep and ambitious framework in modern mathematics that seeks to connect seemingly unrelated areas: number theory, representation theory, and geometry. Proposed by Robert Langlands in a 1967 letter to André Weil, the program suggests a vast network of correspondences between Galois groups, which describe symmetries of number fields, and automorphic forms, which arise from harmonic analysis on groups. At its core, the Langlands Program aims to unify mathematics under a grand “Rosetta Stone” that translates problems in one field into solvable forms in another.

One of the key components is the reciprocity conjecture, which generalizes classical results like class field theory. In this view, every automorphic representation of a reductive group over a global field is expected to correspond to a Galois representation. This conjecture builds a bridge between the arithmetic of equations and the analysis of symmetries on geometric spaces. In practical terms, it suggests that understanding the solutions to certain polynomial equations could come from analyzing harmonic patterns on symmetric spaces.

The Langlands Program has had far-reaching implications. It has driven progress in fields such as algebraic geometry, particularly through the proof of Fermat’s Last Theorem, where Andrew Wiles relied on a case of the modularity conjecture—an early result within the Langlands framework. The geometric Langlands program, a newer development, extends these ideas to sheaves on algebraic curves and has sparked interactions between mathematics and theoretical physics, especially quantum field theory and string theory.

Despite its abstract nature and formidable complexity, the Langlands Program remains one of the most inspiring and unifying visions in mathematics. It invites collaboration across diverse domains and continues to guide mathematicians toward uncovering the hidden symmetries underlying arithmetic and geometry. Its promise of unity offers not just technical insight, but a philosophical sense of harmony within the mathematical universe.

The Boy Who Harnessed the Wind" tells the inspiring true story of William Kamkwamba, a young Malawian boy who built a windmill to save his village from famine. Facing drought and hunger, William, with limited resources and a passion for science, taught himself how to build a windmill from scrap materials. His invention brought electricity and running water to his village, demonstrating the power of innovation and determination in overcoming adversity.

People with disabilities aren’t your charity project, inspirational quote, or social media token. They’re human — living, working, thinking, dreaming — just like you, with a little less sugarcoating and a lot more reality checks.

Disability isn’t a tragedy.
What’s tragic is a world designed by able-bodied people that forgets accessibility until it’s an afterthought.

🛑 Disabilities aren’t always visible.
🛑 They’re not defined by wheelchairs, walking sticks, or stereotyped "sad music" ads.
🛑 And they’re not here to teach you a life lesson about gratitude.

The world constantly overlooks the fact that many people with disabilities are entrepreneurs, artists, leaders, students, professionals — adapting to a society that often refuses to adapt back.

The real side effects of ableism?

Underemployment despite talent.

Public spaces lacking basic accessibility.

Constant infantilization or patronizing.

Media either romanticizing or pitying instead of representing authentically.

We don’t need to “fix” people with disabilities. We need to fix the systems, mindsets, and barriers that disable them further.

So if you really support the disability community —
✅ Normalize accessibility without applause.
✅ Amplify voices, not stereotypes.
✅ Advocate for rights, not pity.

Because at the end of the day, disability isn’t inability. It’s just another way of navigating a world built for people who forgot to think beyond themselves.

The Tesla Cybertruck is an all-electric pickup truck designed by Tesla featuring a futuristic, angular design with a stainless steel exoskeleton. It includes Tesla Armor Glass, engineered for durability. Available in Single, Dual, and Tri-Motor AWD options, it offers a range of approximately 250 to over 500 miles depending on the model. The Tri-Motor version accelerates from 0 to 60 mph in under 2.9 seconds. It has a towing capacity of up to 14,000 pounds and supports a payload of up to 3,500 pounds. The adaptive air suspension improves ride comfort. Inside, it accommodates six adults with a minimalistic dashboard design featuring a large touch screen for controls. Full self-driving capabilities are expected as an option. Production was initially announced for late 2021, with ongoing updates on timelines. The Cybertruck combines utility with performance, making it a unique entry in the pickup truck market.
